docs.abstract: European officials proposed new disclosure rules meant to make it more difficult for countries to work out special tax-avoidance deals with multinationals.
docs.snippet: European officials proposed new disclosure rules meant to make it more difficult for countries to work out special tax-avoidance deals with multinationals.
docs.lead_paragraph: BERLIN — European Union officials on Wednesday proposed new rules to try to discourage tax-avoidance deals with multinational corporations, which critics say give some countries unfair business advantages.

headline.main: European Union Moves to Limit Special Tax Deals
headline.print_headline: Business Briefing; A Proposal to Limit Tax Deals in the European Union

docs.abstract: A V-shaped unmanned vehicle is the centerpiece of the social network’s plans to connect with the five billion or so people it has yet to reach.
docs.snippet: A V-shaped unmanned vehicle is the centerpiece of the social network’s plans to connect with the five billion or so people it has yet to reach.
docs.lead_paragraph: MENLO PARK, Calif. — In classical mythology, Aquila is the eagle carrying Jupiter’s thunderbolts skyward. At Facebook, it is the code name for a high-flying drone, indicative of the social networking company’s lofty ambitions.

headline.main: Drones Beaming Web Access Are in the Stars for Facebook
headline.print_headline: Drones Beaming Web Access Are in the Stars for Facebook

byline.original: By Quentin Hardy and Vindu Goel

docs.abstract: Unidentified hackers have attacked GreatFire.org, a website that provides access to news websites blocked by China.
docs.snippet: Unidentified hackers have attacked GreatFire.org, a website that provides access to news websites blocked by China.
docs.lead_paragraph: For years, a group of anonymous activists known as GreatFire.org has monitored online censorship in China, provided access to blocked websites and collected messages deleted by censors.

headline.main: Hackers Attack GreatFire.org, a Workaround for Websites Censored in China
headline.print_headline: Hackers Bombard Workaround Websites That Provide Access for Chinese Users

docs.abstract: The new program from Amazon allows customers to reorder household items like laundry detergent and paper towels with the push of a single physical button.
docs.snippet: The new program from Amazon allows customers to reorder household items like laundry detergent and paper towels with the push of a single physical button.
docs.lead_paragraph: Amazon has built a booming business of making it easy to buy things online. It has a patented one-click ordering mechanism. It offers subscription-style services. And on Tuesday, Amazon unveiled a pilot program that allows customers to order items with the push of a single physical button.

headline.main: Amazon Dash Aims to Be a Push-Button Substitute for the Supply Run

docs.abstract: Google just matched Amazon for cheap online storage, with an important difference: While Amazon promises to fetch the cheap data in hours, Google offers to do it in three seconds.
docs.snippet: Google just matched Amazon for cheap online storage, with an important difference: While Amazon promises to fetch the cheap data in hours, Google offers to do it in three seconds.
docs.lead_paragraph: Google is offering a new kind of data storage service – and revealing its cloud computing strategy against Amazon Web Services and Microsoft Azure.

headline.main: Google Offers Cheap Storage for Certain Kinds of Data

docs.abstract: While Amazon can now move its tests from inside a warehouse, the retailer still has a long way to go to realize its vision of autonomous delivery drones.
docs.snippet: While Amazon can now move its tests from inside a warehouse, the retailer still has a long way to go to realize its vision of autonomous delivery drones.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Federal regulators have given Amazon a green light to begin testing drones, but it will most likely take years before the online retailer can start delivering packages from the air to peoples’ homes.

headline.main: Amazon Wins Approval to Test Delivery Drones Outdoors
headline.print_headline: Amazon Wins Approval to Test Delivery Drones Outdoors

docs.abstract: The lead developer of Lantern, a censorship-evading tool, discusses how it works and how it has reacted to the new measures by Chinese Internet regulators.
docs.snippet: The lead developer of Lantern, a censorship-evading tool, discusses how it works and how it has reacted to the new measures by Chinese Internet regulators.
docs.lead_paragraph: In recent months, China’s Internet regulators have further restricted the already limited access that the nation’s 648 million Internet users have to the web. Several Google services, including Gmail and Gchat, have become inaccessible. Virtual private networks, or V.P.N.s, that once let users skirt online censorship have also been blocked.

headline.main: Q. and A.: Adam Fisk on Evading Internet Censorship in China

docs.abstract: While Amazon can now move its tests from inside a warehouse, the retailer still has a long way to go to realize its vision of autonomous delivery drones.
docs.snippet: While Amazon can now move its tests from inside a warehouse, the retailer still has a long way to go to realize its vision of autonomous delivery drones.
docs.lead_paragraph: Federal regulators have given Amazon a green light to begin testing drones, but it will most likely take years before the online retailer can start delivering packages from the air to peoples’ homes, writes Nick Wingfield.

headline.main: Daily Report: F.A.A. Gives Amazon Limited Permission on Drones

docs.abstract: After years of battling traditional players in the television business, the big three streaming services must defend against a variety of new offerings.
